#### FB-157: ScrollSpy active label still right-of-rail after notch re-anchor — `will-change` compositor conflict

**UX Intent:** The active label must join the left-side label gutter, visually stacked with the hover labels. Right-side overflow breaks the navigation affordance and clips long section titles.

**Root Cause:** `will-change: top, left` on `.highlightLabelAnchor` (a `position: fixed` + `transform` element) caused Chrome's GPU compositor to promote the element and bake the `transform: translate(-100% - 1x, -50%)` at promotion time — before React had rendered any label text, when the element had zero rendered width. Subsequent `top`/`left` inline-style updates from `useIsomorphicLayoutEffect` were applied on the compositor thread against that stale snapshot, effectively resolving `-100%` as `0`. The anchor's top-left corner landed at `left: notch.left` (right edge of the rail), and the label flowed rightward off-screen. Re-anchoring the `getBoundingClientRect()` source from the inner tick to the notch container (the prior attempted fix) moved the measured `left` by at most ~12px — invisible against the full-label-width error. The measurement was never the problem. (AP-013)

**Resolution:** Removed `will-change: top, left` from `.highlightLabelAnchor`. Added `display: inline-flex; align-items: center` so the anchor shrink-wraps to label text width, making `-100%` in the transform unambiguous regardless of layout context. Animation performance budget (`will-change: transform, opacity`) stays on `.highlightLabel`, which is the element framer-motion actually animates.

**Pattern extracted → `design-anti-patterns.md` AP-073 (new): `will-change` on `position: fixed` + `transform` elements**
